        TOPOF THE NEWS A7 THE STRAITS TIMES MONDAY, JULY 27, 2020 | | | Cross-border travel Applicatio­ns for two schemes for cross-border travel between Singapore and Malaysia can start on Aug 10. Here is a look at what they entail. WHO ARE THEY FOR? RECIPROCAL GREEN LANE key business travellers, For including chief executive officers, senior executives and diplomats who need to conduct negotiatio­ns on very sensitive business arrangemen­ts. PERIODIC COMMUTING ARRANGEMEN­T Singapore and Malaysia residents For with long-term immigratio­n passes for business and work in the other country, to enter that country for work. They have to be prepared to stay in their country of work for at least three months before going back on home leave. STEPS TRAVELLERS HAVE TO TAKE 1 3 Prospectiv­e travellers have to submit an applicatio­n to travel under either of the schemes. Upon arrival in the other country, they will then have to take another PCR test and be isolated while waiting for the result. They can proceed with their itinerary only after the result is clear. 2 If approved, travellers under both schemes will have to take a pre-departure PCR (polymerase chain reaction) test for
Covid-19. the reciprocal under both schemes Those using
will also have to submit to the relevant authoritie­s of the receiving country a controlled itinerary, and adhere to it. Travellers have to also abide by other mutually agreed terms and prevailing public health measures in both countries. More details will be announced soon. green lane ter a super-spreader event involving a mass gathering by the Tabligh missionary group at a mosque in Kuala Lumpur.
During the MCO, most people were allowed to leave their homes only to buy groceries, food or medicine, and only essential workers such as hospital and supermarke­t staff were allowed to leave their homes daily.
Some businesses were allowed to reopen from May 4 under what was called a conditiona­l MCO, as new cases began to taper off.
From June 10, under the recovery MCO, almost all social, educationa­l, religious, business and economic sectors were allowed to resume operations in stages.
Travel between Malaysia’s 13 states was also allowed to resume.
In a move to enforce recovery MCO measures, the authoritie­s have arrested 617 people for various violations, Mr Ismail said.
Twenty were remanded by police for investigat­ions and 597 were issued fines.
Conducting pub and nightclub operations, which remain prohibited, as well as failure to observe social distancing rules were among the violations that led to their arrests. girlfriend with him on the e-scooter as he was riding on the footpath in Pasir Ris Drive 1.
